SCENARIO
	E-commerce mobile app is seeing large-scale coupon abuse and wallet fraud.
	Attackers are reverse engineering the APK and automating API requests.
	As Senior Manager – Product Security, what do you do?

✅ Step 1 — “I would approach this in four layers — client hardening, API enforcement, abuse detection, and business logic correction. 
Coupon fraud is rarely just a mobile issue — it’s usually weak server-side validation combined with automation.”

🟢 LAYER 1 — CLIENT HARDENING (Raise Attack Cost)
	“Mobile hardening does not prevent fraud entirely, but it increases attacker cost.”
1️⃣ Reverse Engineering Resistance
	• Enable R8/ProGuard
	• Remove debug logs
	• Encrypt sensitive strings
	• Detect tampering
	“However, security must not depend on obfuscation because attackers can still instrument runtime.”

2️⃣ Certificate Pinning
Why?
Attackers often:
	• Intercept traffic
	• Study API structure
	• Replay requests
Pinning slows analysis.
	“Pinning can be bypassed on rooted devices, so backend enforcement is critical.”

3️⃣ Root/Jailbreak Detection
	“We detect rooted devices and flag them in backend risk scoring. Instead of blocking all users, we reduce sensitive actions such as wallet usage or coupon stacking.”

🟡 LAYER 2 — API ENFORCEMENT (The Real Fix)
	“Coupon fraud typically happens because the backend trusts client-provided state.”
	• Coupon eligibility logic done client-side
	• Multiple account creation
	• Replay of coupon API
	• Parameter tampering
	• Race condition exploitation

1️⃣ Server-Side Validation
	• Never trust client eligibility
	• Validate coupon usage count server-side
	• Validate user/account/device combination
	“Eligibility, stacking logic, and limits must be enforced server-side — never client-side.”

2️⃣ Idempotency & Replay Protection
Attackers replay coupon apply API.
Fix:
	• Use nonce
	• Use request signing
	• Use idempotency keys
	• Bind coupon to order session

3️⃣ Rate Limiting & Behavioral Controls
	• Rate limit coupon apply endpoint
	• Detect abnormal request velocity
	• Device fingerprint correlation

🔵 LAYER 3 — ABUSE DETECTION (Very Important in E-commerce)
	“Fraud prevention is continuous — I would implement behavioral analytics.”
	• Track coupon attempts per device
	• Track per IP velocity
	• Correlate accounts sharing devices
	• Detect emulator usage
	“Device fingerprinting combined with anomaly detection significantly reduces automated abuse.”

🔴 LAYER 4 — BUSINESS LOGIC FIX
	“If abuse is large scale, it indicates logic design weakness. I would partner with product teams to redesign coupon rules.”
Examples:
	• One coupon per verified phone number
	• Progressive eligibility
	• Risk-based coupon value
	• Backend state locking
This shows cross-functional leadership.

🎯 FULL POLISHED ANSWER 
	“I would approach coupon fraud in four layers — client hardening, API enforcement, behavioral detection, and business logic redesign.
	On the client side, I would increase attack cost through obfuscation, certificate pinning, and root detection. However, mobile controls are bypassable, so real enforcement must happen server-side.
	At the API layer, I would ensure eligibility logic is entirely server-side, implement rate limiting and idempotency protections, and prevent replay or race condition abuse.
	In parallel, I would deploy behavioral analytics to detect abnormal coupon attempts across devices and accounts.
	Finally, I would work with product teams to redesign coupon logic to reduce systemic abuse opportunities.
	The objective is to shift from reactive blocking to architectural resilience.”
That answer will impress.


🔥 (Tricky Follow-Ups)

❓ Follow-Up 1:
“If attackers bypass pinning using Frida, what do you do?”
Correct direction:
	• Runtime integrity checks
	• Backend risk scoring
	• Detect suspicious patterns
	• Don’t rely on client

❓ Follow-Up 2:
“How do you detect emulator-based abuse?”
Answer:
	• Emulator fingerprint signals
	• Device attestation (SafetyNet / Play Integrity API)
	• Unusual hardware profile patterns

❓ Follow-Up 3:
“What if abuse is coming from legitimate devices?”
Strong answer:
	“Then the issue is incentive design and backend control weakness, not client tampering. We focus on business logic and rate limiting.”

